  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Explosive Ordnance Risk Education, Non-technical survey and Victim needs identification for conflict affected population in Pulka and Dikwa, threatened by the presence of improvised landmines and explosive remnants of war.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Northeast Nigeria is facing a landmine crisis as a result of the ongoing conflict between non-state armed groups and the Nigerian Army. From 1 January 2016 to 31 August 2019, 806 people were injured and killed by landmines and other explosive remnants of war.  Casualty figures averaged 25 people per month during this period, over a third of whom were civilians. Nigeria is among the countries with the highest casualty rates in the world. 
The majority of the incidents are improvised items, such as locally manufactured landmines and other explosive devices deployed by organized armed groups. However, contamination from conventional weapons after clashes between government forces and non-state armed groups, including mortars, rockets and grenades, also poses a risk to communities. 
The impact of landmines and other explosive remnants of war drives communities from their home and restricts the use of land for productive use. It exacerbates a significant humanitarian crisis &#x2013; with over 7 million people in humanitarian need in northeast Nigeria &#x2013; by denying access to assistance at the same time as it restricts humanitarian access to vulnerable communities. 
This project aims to address this landmine emergency by tailoring an integrated approach to humanitarian mine action, by delivering life-saving Risk Education to IDPs, refugees and host communities (adults and children), identifying EO victims in Dikwa and Pulka and collecting information on contamination in northeast Nigeria through Non-Technical Survey (NTS) and Remote Contamination Baseline Assessments (RCBA). MAG will also explore partnerships with an INGO and national NGO to expand the impact, reach and sustainability of the project.</narrative>
  </description>
